                    <h5 style="text-align: left;margin-bottom: 10px">Student Loneliness: The Role of Social Media Through Life Transitions – Lisa Thomas, Elizabeth Ormea, Finola Kerrigan</h5>
                    <p class="text-left">In this article, the authors report findings from a survey of 510 first year undergraduates across the UK, identifying factors that predict student loneliness, and exploring their social media use. Higher levels of social capital, induction satisfaction, and sense of community are associated with lower levels of loneliness. It is found that there is a negative relationship between the liminal self-measure, and student loneliness. This indicates that students are less likely to experience loneliness throughout the transition to university when they do not censor their previous online identity during the transition. The authors suggested that the use of social media can help students to stay connected to old friends and relationships.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

